ce:section.ce:para:
In order to validate the E. coli stock solution, the colony-forming units (CFU) were determined using the UV absorbance method combined with the standard plate count technique. The culture was subjected to a dilution process, wherein 990 μL of water were admixed with 10 μL of the culture, resulting in a 1:100 dilution, also known as a 10−2 dilution factor. Subsequently, aliquots of the initial dilution were subjected to further dilutions, generating a 10−4 dilution, accomplished by withdrawing 10 μL from the 10−2 dilution and introducing it to 990 μL of water. The diluted samples were then plated onto petri dishes. Similar dilution and plating procedures were replicated in two separate trials, and the respective bacterial counts were depicted in Fig. 5
                           . Following the incubation of the petri plates at 37°C, the colonies were enumerated within the range of 30 to 300 colonies, ensuring countability. Based on the maximum possible colony counts, the CFU for the original E. coli stock solution was determined to be 2.05 × 109 CFU/mL (see Table 1
                           ).
